UNICEF Data Analysis on Global Stillbirth Rates By Mehetabel Ojienor

Stillbirth is a silent crisis

Every year, millions of babies are lost before they take their first breath, yet the issue remains largely overlooked in global health discussions. These preventable tragedies are not evenly spread they disproportionately affect lower-income countries, regions with weak health infrastructure, and populations facing systemic inequality. This analysis aims to uncover the patterns and disparities in global stillbirth rates, using data from the UNICEF database.

merged_world = world.merge(merged, left_on='ADMIN', right_on='country')


import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(20, 12))
merged_world.plot(column='obs_value', cmap='coolwarm', linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor='0.8', legend=True)
plt.title('Global Map of Stillbirth Rates', fontsize=15)
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

🌍 Global Distribution of Stillbirth Rates

The distribution of stillbirth rates by country is depicted on the world map above.
The intensity of the colour indicates the magnitude of the stillbirth rate; larger rates are indicated by deeper hues.

My key Observations

  • High Stillbirth Rates:
    Countries in Sub-Saharan Africa, such as Nigeria, Chad, and the Central African Republic, exhibit some of the highest stillbirth rates globally.

  • Moderate Stillbirth Rates:
    Parts of South Asia, including Pakistan and Afghanistan, also show moderately high stillbirth rates compared to global averages.

  • Lower Stillbirth Rates:
    Countries in Europe, North America, and East Asia, such as Germany, the United States, and Japan, display significantly lower stillbirth rates.

Regional Disparities

There is a clear geographical pattern: - Africa faces the highest burden, reflecting challenges in access to quality maternal and neonatal healthcare. - Developed regions show lower stillbirth rates, likely due to better healthcare infrastructure, higher socioeconomic conditions, and more advanced medical technologies.

In conclusion, this map highlights critical regions that require urgent interventions to address preventable stillbirths.
Targeted investments in maternal healthcare systems, education, and access to skilled birth attendants could substantially reduce these disparities.

merged['obs_value'] = pd.to_numeric(merged['obs_value'], errors='coerce')
Code 
# Force obs_value into numeric
merged['obs_value'] = pd.to_numeric(merged['obs_value'], errors='coerce')

# Top 10 Countries
top10 = merged.groupby('country')['obs_value'].mean().nlargest(10).reset_index()

# Bar Chart
from plotnine import *

(
    ggplot(top10, aes(x='reorder(country, obs_value)', y='obs_value')) +
    geom_col(fill='skyblue') +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(title='Top 10 Countries by Stillbirth Rate', x='Country', y='Stillbirth Rate')
)

Most countries listed are in Sub-Saharan Africa, which may reflect broader challenges in maternal and neonatal healthcare systems across the region. Socioeconomic factors, access to healthcare, and public health infrastructure likely play major roles in influencing these outcomes. These findings underline the urgent need for targeted interventions and healthcare improvements in the most affected countries.

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, theme_minimal, labs


(
    ggplot(merged.to_pandas()) +
    aes(x='time_period', y='obs_value') +
    geom_point(color='blue', size=0.7, alpha=0.4) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color='red', size=1.2, se=True) +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
        title='Relationship Between Time Period and Stillbirth Rate',
        x='Year',
        y='Stillbirth Rate'
    )
)

Poverty and Stillbirth: A Clear Link

The scatterplot illustrates a strong inverse relationship between wealth and stillbirth rates. Countries with higher GDP per capita tend to have significantly lower stillbirth rates, highlighting the role of economic resources in access to better healthcare. Wealthier countries may invest more in infrastructure, maternity health services, and newborn care, which directly lowers avoidable fatalities. This pattern highlights global health inequity. On the other hand, structural obstacles in low-income nations continue to endanger mothers and infants.

From my graph it shows that the average stillbirth rate in Nigeria has remained relatively stable between 1960 and 2020.This is visually represented by a mostly flat trend line, indicating little to no major changes in average stillbirth rates over the sixty-year period. The lack of significant progress highlights the need for more targeted interventions and investments in healthcare systems to reduce preventable stillbirths.

Conclusion

This report examined global stillbirth rates using UNICEF data, highlighting critical structural patterns across countries and regions.
Rather than showing uniform progress, the data reveal uneven improvements, with high-burden regions such as Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia lagging behind wealthier nations.

  • The stability of stillbirth rates in countries like Nigeria shows that national averages can mask internal disparities and persistent healthcare challenges.
  • The scatterplot analysis reinforces that economic growth alone is insufficient without targeted maternal and neonatal health strategies.

Recommendations

To effectively reduce stillbirth rates, countries must focus on:

  • Deliberate policy interventions,
  • Healthcare system strengthening, and
  • Localized approaches that address specific regional and cultural barriers.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
